Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa announced there will be an ease in lockdown restrictions. From 30 April, the country is expected to begin a gradual and phased resumption of economic activity, according to Ramaphosa. "We will implement what we call a risk-adjusted strategy, through which we take a deliberate and cautious approach to the easing of the current lockdown regulations", said Ramaphosa. READ: Ramaphosa announces 6-months coronavirus relief grant From Friday 1 May South Africa will move to lockdown level 4. Bars and shebeens to remain closed. Level 4 lockdown permits the sale of cigarettes. Courtesy #DStv403 Ramaphosa's address comes after he unveiled a R500-billion relief plan aimed at assisting South Africans during the COVID-19 pandemic. The president announced the 21-day lockdown on Monday, 23 March and it officially began on midnight Thursday evening, 26 March. The lockdown was extended for a further two weeks in early April. There are currently 3,953 COVID-19 confirmed cases in South Africa with 75 fatalities. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs. Will South Africa stay on a hard lockdown, or will we see industries re-opening in a phased approach?